<ul>
<li><strong>Miners</strong>: Validate transactions and secure the network.</li>



<li><strong>Developers</strong>: Maintain and upgrade Bitcoin&#8217;s protocol.</li>



<li><strong>Users</strong>: Drive the demand and value of the token.</li>



<li><strong>Exchanges</strong>: Facilitate the trading of Bitcoin, impacting liquidity and price.</li>



<li><strong>Regulators</strong>: Can influence Bitcoin&#8217;s utility through policy.</li>
</ul>



<p>Each group wields influence, but none can unilaterally dictate Bitcoin&#8217;s direction. Mastery of this decentralized dance is crucial for you to thrive in the cryptocurrency domain.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">How are changes made to Bitcoin core?</h3>



<p>Understanding who controls Bitcoin is essential.</p>



<p> Similarly, knowing how changes are made to the core of the cryptocurrency sheds light on the governance that Dogecoin must navigate to ensure compliance.</p>



<p>You, as a power-seeking individual investing in Dogecoin, must grasp that Bitcoin&#8217;s protocol evolves through a decentralized process. It starts with proposals (BIPs) which are meticulously scrutinized by developers and the community.</p>



<p>When you mine Dogecoin or engage in Dogecoin mining, you&#8217;re part of a similar ecosystem where updates reflect consensus, akin to the Bitcoin model. The founders of Dogecoin have set a precedent, but today&#8217;s changes hinge on majority agreement.</p>



<p>Converting Dogecoin to Bitcoin or vice versa, you&#8217;re subject to the underlying protocols refined through this collective decision-making.</p>



